    section#sleep_patterns
      h1 sleep patterns: <br>a tactile sound interface for sleep. (2009)
      // === Portfolio comment. ============
      section.comment(style="display:none")
        p The experimental sound interface Sleep Patterns produces drones for sleeping in response to the movement of long hair-like threads on its surface. By combing, shifting and twisting these individual "hairs", varying tones and rhythmic patterns emerge. Inviting to the touch, the Sleep Patterns interface encourages interaction in the gallery and between participants.
        p The system is a supplement to sleep; a device that one can reach over and tussle until a pleasing drone is found, then fall peacefully back to sleep. The interface is a block with "hairs" of conductive thread as the major point of interaction.
      // === Portfolio entry. ============
      dl.gallery
        dt.type <em>Physical interactive media installation</em>
        dd.info <em>Role:</em> <span>Lead artist</span>
        dd.info <em>Tech:</em> <span>Conductive thread, MaxMSP and Jitter with custom wiring and hardware</span>
        dt <hr>
        dd.description Produced interactive sculpture as an "imperfect interface" where you could never count on reproducing the same response twice through the arrangement of hundreds of individual threads
        dt <hr>
        dd.slideshow
          | <a href="https://s3.amazonaws.com/louisrawlins-portfolio/galleries/sleep_patterns/sleep_patterns_small.jpg" rel="lightbox[sleep_patternsInstall]" title="Sleep Patterns"><img class="thumb" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/louisrawlins-portfolio/galleries/sleep_patterns/sleep_patterns_small.jpg" /></a>

